Fix group_authority representation in repr

The current `__repr__` implementation of `Aarc_g002_entitlement` is
assuming that the `group_authority` is always defined and present.
However, this is not always the case. In the cases that the
`group_authority` is not defined `#None` will be displayed as a suffix
of the `repr` result. To fix this, we check whether `group_authority` is
defined and only if that condition is met we display it, exactly as is
already done with `role`.

Fix strict regex and is_contained_in/__le__

- subgroups are optional
- role is optional

The group might not be followed by any of the two - it should look out
for "#" along with ":".

Applying the same logic for the subgroups - the regex should look out
for "#" along with ":".

Finally, the role should not take over the group-authority, but should
look out for the first "#".

---

Fixing the regex relevealed a faulty test case:
- TestAarc_g002_entitlement::test_subgroup_required

Previously, `req_entitlement` would _not_ be recognized as an aarc-g002
entitlement. `is_contained_in` would be handled by the non-g002 handler.

Fixing the regex to recognize the req_entitlement as an g002-entitlement
revealed a bug in `is_contained_in`/`__le__`. The subgroups of self should
be checked, not the subgroups of other. All of the subgroups of
req_entitlement should also exist in other.
